Preheat your oven to 180 C. Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} to the boil for the potato. Trim the @courgette{1} then halve lengthways. Slice widthways into roughly 2cm slices, then pop the courgette and @cherry plum tomatoes{200} in a large #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Arrange in a single layer, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, chop the @potatoes{450}(no need to peel) into 2cm chunks. Pop the chunks into the saucepan of boiling water and cook for ~{6-8%minutes}.

> The potato is done when you can easily slip a knife through.

When cooked, drain into a #colander{} and set aside.

In the meantime, zest the @lemon{1/2} and chop into wedges. Pick the @thyme{1/2}(leaves picked from stalks and roughly chopped) and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Bash the @garlic clove{1} with the flat of your knife and chop in half (leave the skins on!).

Place each @coley fillet{2} on a #chopping board{}. Season both sides with @salt{}, @pepper{} and lemon zest. Drizzle with a little @oil{} then, using your hands, rub the seasoning into the fish. Wrap one piece of @serrano ham{2} around the middle of each fillet. When the veggies have been in the oven for ~{20%minutes}, carefully place the fish on top of them and return to the oven for ~{8-10%minutes}.

> The fish is cooked when opaque in the centre.

While your fish is in the oven, heat a good glug of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, carefully add your drained potatoes, garlic and thyme. Fry until golden and crispy, stirring occasionally, ~{8-10%minutes}. When they are golden, squeeze the juice from one of the lemon wedges into the pan along with a good knob of @?butter{knob}. Bubble away for ~{30%seconds}, then remove from the heat. Set aside.

When your fish is ready, divide the garlicky potatoes between your plates and place a fillet on top. Serve with the roasted veggies on the side and any roasting juices poured over the top. Dig in!